<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title></title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">FBA0022/13-14</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">ACCA</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">—</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">About ACCA</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ACCA </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">is the global body for professional accountants. We aim to offer business-relevant, first-choice qualifications to people around the world who seek a rewarding career in accountancy, finance and management.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">support our 162,000 members and 428,000 students in 173 countries helping them to develop successful careers in accounting and business, with the skills needed by employers. We work through a network of over 89 offices and centres and 8,500 Approved Employ</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ers worldwide, who provide high standards of employee learning and development. Through our public interest remit, we promote appropriate regulation of accounting and conduct relevant research to ensure accountancy continues to grow in reputation and influ</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ence.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The expertise of our senior members and in-house technical experts allows ACCA to provide informed opinion on a range of financial, regulatory, public sector and business areas, including: taxation (business and personal); small business; pensions; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">education; and corporate governance and corporate social responsibility. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">The</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline"> new approach to tax policy making</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:14pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 14pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In March 2011, the Treasury Committee set out six principles by which it recommended tax policy should be measured. This memorandum seeks to comment at a high level on the extent to which recent governmental activity, and in particular the December 2013 dr</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">aft clauses, coincide with those principles. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The Principles are that tax policy should:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">1.      be fair. The Committee accepts that not all commentators will agree on the detail of what constitutes a fair tax, but a tax system which is considered to be fu</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ndamentally unfair will ultimately fail to command consent.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">2.      </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">support</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> growth and encourage competition.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">3.      </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">provide</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> certainty. In virtually all circumstances the application of the tax rules </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">should</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> be certain. It should not normally be </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">necessary for anyone to resort to the courts in order to resolve how the rules operate in relation to his or her tax affairs.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">4.      </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">provide</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> stability. Changes to the underlying rules should be kept to a minimum and policy shocks should both be avoided. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">There should be a justifiable economic and/or social basis for any change to the tax rules and this justification should be made public and the underlying policy made clear.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">5.      The Committee also considers that it is important that a person's tax lia</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">bility should be easy to calculate and straightforward and cheap to collect. To this end, tax policy should be practicable.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">6.      Finally, the tax system as a whole must be coherent. New provisions should complement the existing tax system, not conflict</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> with it.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">As the Committee has observed, while principles can be separate into “basic” and “procedural” types, in practice there is considerable overlap between them, and tax policy needs to follow all the principles to be “good” policy. Given constraints</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> of time on both the authors and the readership, we have focused on a few key proposals to illustrate the principles.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In this connection, ACCA has published a paper, attached at Appendix A, which goes into some further detail in attempting to identify the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> key themes which policy makers should address in seeking Simplicity in their tax systems, addressing in particular the areas covered by the Committee’s fifth and sixth points. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">A key consideration highlighted in that paper is the evidence from a World Ba</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">nk survey of international business pointing to the greater importance of simplicity in tax systems as a factor encouraging growth, rather than the focus on rates alone. Though not yet scientifically tested there seem to be a clear preference in business f</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">or certainty and stability in the system. Businesses value the efficiency and predictability of a higher tax rate more than they do the cash which might, possibly, come their way if they have the stamina and resource to deal with a complex system potential</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ly offering lower rates. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">With this in mind, it is particularly important that we have better tax legislation and a more coherent series of policy objectives for the taxes which are in place. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Tax rates – while the quantum of tax rates is beyond the scop</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">e of the FBSC review, it is notable that the structure of corporation tax rates has been simplified since 2010, with a view to aligning the rates of corporation tax paid by all sizes of business. While this degree of simplification is of course welcomed, i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">t comes at the price of the original underlying policy rationale of supporting smaller business through lower tax burdens, and in order to maintain that differential support of SMEs, reforms to the NICs regime have become a feature of recent Finance Bills,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> seeking to extend investment incentives focussed particularly on employment, at smaller businesses. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Such incentives themselves introduce an element of further complexity, although the levels of this are varied. The Regional Employer NICs Holiday scheme </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">was seen by most commentators as unduly complicated, and has been widely categorised as a failure with an extremely low take-up. The replacement scheme, which removes the first £2,000 of employer NICs contributions for every business, is a far simpler and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">broader measure, which has nevertheless been categorised as unfairly benefitting businesses in the Southeast, on the basis that a greater number of businesses based in and around London will be excluded altogether form making employer NICs contributions th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">at in other regions. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In terms of administration and simplification though the new measure is far more successful, not least because it can be quickly and simply integrated into the RTI reporting system used for submission of all employers’ payroll inform</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ation to HMRC. By setting the amount at a fixed level it has a proportionally greater impact for smaller businesses, and the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">decision not to set any thresholds for eligibility, or to attempt to implement </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">clawback</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> mechanisms for la</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">r</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ger business, retain the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">simplicity of the model. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">SMEs have been a focus of government policy, and measures seeking to assist the smallest businesses have been a feature of each budget under the current government.  A key element of the administrative focus has been the drive to digital channels of admini</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">stration, but there has been mixed success for these initiatives. The aim of greater scrutiny driving better legislation has suffered setbacks in this area. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">As part of the move to increase online filing of business taxes, filing of all VAT returns by ele</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ctronic means was made mandatory from 1 April 2012, with only the most limited of exemptions. However, the policy and legislation was challenged by a number of taxpayers exhibiting comparatively common characteristics which made online filing difficult for</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> them. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Of particular relevance to the current debate was the finding of the Tax Tribunal that the HMRC Impact Assessment process had been insufficient, failing as it did to adequately address the issues raised in the appeals. In particular, the pragmatic</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> solution adopted by HMRC of setting up a telephone filing service, but seeking to restrict demand for it, was criticised by the tribunal. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">More recently, HMRC has issued a consultation document calling for views on the implementation of paperless Self-As</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">sessment for Income Tax. While the specific subject matter of the consultation, an enabling regulation, was perhaps not in itself susceptible to detailed discussion, the broader issues around the area, which the consultation document did seek to raise awar</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">eness of, undeniably need greater attention than was feasible in the 4 weeks allowed for responses – particularly in view of the fact that the 4 week period (27 November – 27 December 2013) encompassed the Autumn Statement, the release of the draft clauses</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, and Christmas. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The concern that responses to the consultation may not be fully factored into design of subsequent systems is heightened by the knowledge that trials of the new system are to commence on a limited basis in February 2014, and be rolled ou</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">t for general use in April 2014. ACCA supports the use of technology to reduce administrative costs and burdens for HMRC, taxpayers and their agents alike. However the proposals are aimed principally at individual Self-Assessment taxpayers. It seems unlike</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ly that any useful feedback on the wider implications of a fully online self-assessment process can be gleaned from an 8 week period, during which a typical self-assessment taxpayer will not receive much in the way of communications from HMRC. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Moreover, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the trial is being conducted only with volunteers – given that the paperless option is itself to be voluntary to start with this seems reasonable enough, but our concern is that ultimately the paperless option will (as with VAT) become compulsory. At that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">point, a system designed over a short period of time and based upon input from positively focussed volunteers may well prove to exhibit design features, or flaws, which render it unsuitable for wider use. Such shortcomings are far more likely to be flushed</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> out by a lengthy and widely publicised consultation process.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> It should be noted that HMRC’s inability to pursue a more measured course may be the result of outside influences on timetable. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">A further feature of HMRC’s drive to move systems and processes</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> on line is that Agent Strategy work. While this has mostly been evidenced in Finance Bills through comparatively brief aspects of administrative legislation, the overall impact on the administration of taxes in the UK is likely to be considerable. As more</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and more of HMRCs own systems are streamlined and moved to entirely digital process, so the potential benefits of allowing taxpayers and their agents to interact directly with those systems increase.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">However, there are clear security implications of allo</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">wing individuals and agents access to government systems and records. There is a concern that the challenges of implementing a suitably robust system may be too great to overcome within the ambitious timeframes set out for offering enhanced access to taxpa</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">yer information and records. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The overall process of consultation on tax legislation has shown some signs of improvement, but is still very much a curate’s egg. The most recent iteration of the Cabinet Office guidelines on public consultation allow for co</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">nsultation periods of between 2-12 weeks, but give no clear guidance or examples on what timeframe might be suitable for which measures, in contrast to the July 2012 version of the guidance, which suggested that 12 weeks might be adequate for full public c</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">onsultation on </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">eg</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> a new policy for nuclear power in the UK. Although the Cabinet Office website acknowledges the existence of a 2012 edition of the guidance, it (along with the superseded 2008 guidance) cannot be accessed from anywhere on the Cabinet Offic</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">e website or the National Archives. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Tax, including its consultation process, does not exist in a vacuum. A key element of effective consultation is publicity for and accessibility of the consultation documents </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">themselves</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. It is a matter of regret therefo</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">re that the transition of departmental consultation pages to the central gov.uk site seems to have significantly reduced the visibility of consultations. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">A review of the site documented by a former member of HMRC’s own policy team highlighted a number of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> significant shortcomings in the new site when compared to the previous HMRC pages, including the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">apparent </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">failure of many consultations to appear at all in listings. When combined with the shorter timeframes allocated under the current iteration of the Ca</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">binet Office principles on consultation there is a concern that not all consultations are accessible to all concerned individuals. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The emphasis on digital delivery of the consultation process runs the risk of introducing a bias against the digitally excl</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">uded in the consultation process. While the tax system applies to all residents of the UK, digitally aware or not, the process of consulting on that system should be open to all residents in the same way.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">While many tax consultations have retained the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">full 12 week period, there is one stark example of a reduced period, being the draft Finance Bill Clauses themselves (which do not appear on the gov.uk ‘consultation’ pages; they are listed under ‘publications’</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. While it may be the case that much of the m</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">aterial has been exposed to previous scrutiny, it is nevertheless the case that the 8 calendar week consultation period (which is reduced to less </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">than 7 weeks by the Cabinet Office allowance for the Christmas holiday period) is not sufficient to allow for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">full scrutiny of all the detail of the legislation. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The issue is of course exacerbated for many practising accountants by the coincidence with the personal tax filing deadline, and the preponderance of businesses which run to a December year end necessit</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ating corporate tax filings in December and in many cases audit work in January. The situation is undoubtedly better than it was before the publication of full draft clauses, but the timetable is still far from perfect. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="24" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">A step back from the constant chan</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ges to the tax system would have the twofold benefits of delivering the stability which business yearns for while releasing the energies currently devoted by HMRC and accountants alike to developing and dealing with change for more socially useful activiti</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">es, such as tackling tax evasion on the one hand, and advising clients on how to make more profit (rather than calculating the tax due on profits already made). </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="25" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">There have been clear examples of the consultation process working. In the summer of 2012, pr</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">oposals were put forward for a tax on ‘controlling persons’ as a development of the existing suite of rules aimed at ensuring appropriate taxation of income as deriving from employment or enterprise. Following consultation, the (widely criticised) proposal</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s were withdrawn and more limited measures, within the existing legal framework, adopted. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="26" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">However, the taxation of individuals on the borderlines of employment/self-employment, especially when allied to the ability in the UK of a business to ‘buy’ the ri</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ght to taxation as a return on capital (dividends) rather than a return on labour, remains problematic. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="27" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The difficulties posed by the (literally) offshore oil sector have provoked their own legislation, and their own consultation process. At the same tim</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">e, the labour market response to the complex interaction of UK and EU tax and employment rules has seen a growth inter alia in purported self-employment under ‘umbrella’ companies. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="28" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">While the HMRC team dealing with design of the implementing legislation s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">eem clear in their aim not to disrupt existing commercial arrangements for genuine businesses, the nature of the interactions between tax, company and employment law is such that drawing the distinction between genuine and abusive structures may not be via</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ble. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="29" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Moreover, the cost implications in some sectors of imposing the new system could have far wider impacts on growth and employment patterns. The effect of the new proposals would be to increase labour costs in some sectors such as construction by up t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">o </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">15</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">%, and there simply is not a margin of that size available anywhere in the supply chain to absorb such extra costs. Labour supply in construction is highly cost sensitive, and an effective pay cut for the existing labour force would be unthinkable; eit</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">her construction costs (including government infrastructure projects) will increase, or cheaper alternative labour will be sought. Tax does not exist in a vacuum, and tax policy can have wider long term effects.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Taxation of partnerships </span><br /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline"> </span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 14pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Specific pro</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">visions of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Sch</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> 1,2,3,4 </span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 14pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">1)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Partnerships have been identified by HMRC as an area where existing tax provisions are particularly susceptible to abuse. While it is of course important that abuse is targeted and counteracted, it is important that the pursuit of wrongdoing is not allowed</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> to cloud HMRC judgement in seeking to frame changes to tax treatment which will have significant commercial impact on otherwise compliant taxpayers. </span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 14pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">2)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In the impact assessments, the new provisions are consistently described as ensuring that affected indivi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">duals ‘will now be required to pay the correct amount of tax and NICs at broadly the right time’. As a matter of legislative interpretation, it might be considered impossible for the existing provisions to ensure that the wrong amount of tax is collected, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">but if, as appears to be the case, the existing provisions allow the ‘wrong amount’ of tax to be paid, or at the ‘wrong time’ then it is the legislation, or the individuals taking advantage of it, which are at fault. The compliant majority of partnerships </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">are not at fault, and should not suffer either materially or </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">reputationally</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> as a result of their choice of business form.     </span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 14pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Part 1, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Salaried</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> members</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 14pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">3)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">There is an underlying structural trend to the broader relationship between taxpayer and state that entr</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">epreneurs who take the risks and rewards of self-employment pay a lower burden in taxes to the State. However, they are also entitled to fewer tax-funded benefits from the State, and many of the legal protections available to employees are not available to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> the self-employed. It is of course the case that they are not really appropriate in the business relationship between a self-employed individual and their customers/trading partners, as the counterparty will not have assumed the responsibilities which are</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> attendant upon an employer. Conversely, employees, who are granted a higher level of statutory protections and State benefits, pay a higher price in taxation. </span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 14pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">4)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Accordingly, if the true nature of the relationship is one of employment, rather than entrepren</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">eurial assumption of risk on the part of the ‘partner’ then it is perhaps reasonable to reflect this in the taxation of the parties to the relationship. But the corollary to imposing the burden of employee taxation on the relationship should be extending t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">he corresponding benefits of it to the parties. It should be the case that those being taxed as employees are treated for all purposes as employees and not simply the case that the payments are taxed ‘as if they were employment income’. </span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 14pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">5)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The payment should</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> become employment income, and the individuals treated in every way as employees (and the LLP as employer). If that is the legal reality then it should apply as such in every aspect of the State’s relationship with the parties to the relevant contract. Whe</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">re LLP membership has been imposed as an abusive treatment of low paid workers, the additional imposition of employment taxes without extension of the full protections of employment status in law could effectively place the workers in a worse position than</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> before. </span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 14pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">6)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In terms of the practical application of the 3 tests, there are a number of potential practical issues. While it is understandable that the existing Employment Status Manual </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Tests have been rejected as in inappropriate in a significant proportion</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> of partnership cases (as they do not take adequate account of capital contributions in a partnership context) the shift to a new test will inevitably introduce some element of short term uncertainty. </span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 14pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">7)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">There is likely to be a degree of uncertainty in the l</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">onger term arising out of the introduction of a new test of ‘significant influence’ in the legislation, which is not further defined in the legislation. While HMRC guidance is welcome in this area, the fact remains that this will of course not be binding a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">nd greater certainty for taxpayers must wait upon judicial pronouncement.</span><br /></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 14pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">8)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">While the quanta of the two financial tests will always </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">be</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> subject to debate, there is a more fundamental aspect of their measurement which is likely to give rise to some practical </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">administrative difficulty for partnerships. The measurement of fixed/variable salary appears from the guidance to be tied to the partnership’s accounting year, which aligns with the usual allocation of profits. The measurement of salary by reference to cap</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ital contribution however falls to be measured over the fiscal year, which may or may not align with the partnerships accounting year. The inconsistency in measurement will impose an administrative burden for any partnerships which account other than on th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">e fiscal year, doubling the number of calculations required.</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 14pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Part 2, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Mixed</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> memberships</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 14pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">9)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Underlying these provisions is the difficult policy question of whether LLPs should have a level playing field with other corporate bodies when accumulating reserves for future investment. A growing company will retain profits after deduction of corporatio</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">n tax at the appropriate rates; to the extent that its members are individuals an LLP will lose the additional capacity to invest equivalent to the additional income tax and NICs. </span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 14pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">10)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The counter proposition is of course that individual members can effectivel</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">y defer an element of their personal tax liability if they can divert profits to a personally controlled corporate member of the partnership. Equally, if partnerships are presumed to be transparent on the part of the partner, there should be no policy obje</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ction to taxing the profits arising relate to investment of capital on the basis otherwise set down in law for returns to capital, in the knowledge that this will incur a corresponding loss of State benefits and statutory entitlements. </span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 14pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">11)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Once again, we find</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> ourselves quickly exposing the bedrock of tax principles – should returns on capital be taxed at a differential rate to returns on labour? And should entrepreneurial returns be taxed at a differential rate to employed labour? Currently the position in the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> UK is that an individual can effectively ‘buy the right’ to capital tax treatment on returns by purchasing or setting up a limited company, a relatively cheap and trivial operation. Having once established the machinery for transmission of funds under the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> guise of returns on capital, it becomes a question of fact in each individual case whether that treatment is actually in line with the legal provisions of the taxing acts. </span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 14pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">12)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Analysis of the intention of Parliament when considering the taxation of returns o</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">n capital, or ‘unearned income’, is notoriously complex as legislation and case law may span </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">many decades and radical shifts in policy intent, and indeed rates of taxation which can fundamentally change the impact of given provisions over time. </span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 14pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">13)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The mere f</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">act that a mechanism can be abused is not in itself justification for outlawing it, if there also </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">exist</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> legitimate and indeed beneficial uses for that mechanism. Accordingly any restriction on the use of the mechanism should be appropriate and proportionat</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">e, and not unduly hamper legitimate activities. However, the proposals as drafted would effectively prevent LLPs from accruing reserves at the same rates as other limited liability trading vehicles, since any control on the part of the members of the partn</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ership over the corporate member would subject all those profits to the differential taxation which the mechanism seeks to counteract. Equally, the partnership as a body of individuals with a common aim could not reasonably be expected to pass control of t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">he partnership profits to a totally unconnected and uncontrollable third party. </span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 14pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">14)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The provisions in relation to allocation of losses appear less potentially controversial given that loss allocation is more likely to be tax motivated in its entirety.</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 14pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Part 3,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> AIFM partnerships deferred remuneration</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 14pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">15)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">As befits the complexity of the underlying provisions which require the adjustments to the tax accounting in respect of deferred remuneration, the partnerships provisions (especially in respect of capital gains tax </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">treatment) appear initially complex. However, it is relevant in this context that those partnerships and individuals involved in this aspect of the tax system should by definition be financially literate and able to deal with complicated legislation. </span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 14pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">16)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">One </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">aspect which may be of commercial concern to those partnerships affected is the treatment of deferred remuneration which does not ultimately vest. In such cases, the Exchequer will retain the initial payment of tax at 45%, but will in addition collect tax </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">at the appropriate rate from any further member to whom the available funds are allocated, effectively subjecting the partnership to double taxation on those profits. </span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 14pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">17)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">While there may be some policy justification behind such provisions to curtail the award</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> of unrealistic or utterly speculative awards, there is nevertheless a concern that in the event of a significant market fall, effectively preventing any managers from achieving their targets, the partnership (which is already likely to be in financial dif</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ficulty) will have suffered a heavier burden of taxation than an equivalent business not subject to the rules. </span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 14pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">18)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Part 4, Disposal of assets through partnerships</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 14pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">19)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The taxation of capital assets in partnerships is equally an area of difficulty for partners and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> tax practitioners alike. The targeted anti-avoidance rule proposed in the relevant provisions of the draft Finance Bill consider a comparatively restricted subset of possible transactions within the partnership itself, and should by their nature be applic</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">able only in limited circumstances. While they are potentially burdensome in application, the reliance upon an ‘intention’ test should restrict their imposition to those situations where taxpayers are deliberately seeking an advantage by means of contrived</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and artificial mechanisms, thereby levelling the playing field for compliant taxpayers. As such, the complexity can be rationalised, but as is a theme of the OTS Interim Report on Partnerships) </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">there would be a broader benefit in wider simplification of t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">he tax regime for partnerships based upon a clear recognition by HMRC and policy makers of the difficulties caused by the current failure to clearly and explicitly address the issues faced by one of the most popular and important business structures in the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> UK’s economy. </span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 14pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Broader policy considerations</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 14pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">20)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">As is noted by the OTS Interim Report, to which Chas Roy-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Chowdhury</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, ACCA head of taxation contributed as a member of the Consultative Committee, the taxation of partnerships generally is an area where the techn</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ical complexities of dealing with an extremely flexible and diverse vehicle are exacerbated by the administrative difficulties of the law and policy being at times difficult to identify. A more coordinated approach to the presentation of the tax law on par</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">tnerships, and clearer lines of communication with, and within, HMRC would help to resolve many of the practical difficulties which aggravate the compliance burden for partnerships. </span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 14pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">21)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The problems are particularly pronounced for smaller partnerships underta</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">king the sorts of transactions which, while significant and (across the population as a whole) perhaps relatively common, they will only enter into exceptionally – for example, introduction of new members/capital, or departure of the same. Uncertainty or i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">gnorance around the tax implications of what will in any case be significant commercial decisions for the partnership should be reduced as far as possible. ACCA fully supports the 12 “Short Term Fixes” identified by the OTS in their Interim Report.</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 14pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">22)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The OTS</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> report also considers the more fundamental step of bringing LLPs within the charge to corporation tax, or alternatively treating them as taxable persons subject to income tax in their own right (with appropriate relief for taxes already paid being given o</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">n subsequent drawings). As the OTS notes, both options would fundamentally change the tax treatment of LLPs away from that envisaged in the original legislation involving significant redrafting. Nevertheless, the quoted example of a purported partnership o</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">f 20,000 members highlights the issues facing HMRC. </span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 14pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">23)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">A longer term review of partnership structures might consider a greater degree of regulation for larger partnerships, along the lines of the differential regulation for different sizes and types of limited liability companies. A requirement for registratio</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">n and returns in respect of any partnership with memberships above a certain threshold might enable HMRC to manage resources and compliance more effectively. While there may be a growth in partnerships manufactured to fall just below the threshold, this wo</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">uld in itself be a factor in risk assessment. Such issues are however matters of business law rather than tax law, and would therefore fall outside the scope of any pure tax review. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">APPENDIX – ACCA Report: Simplicity in the Tax System. Please email </span><a href="mailto:johnsonsa@parliament.uk"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Stephanie Johnson</span></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> if you would like an electronic copy.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">January 2014</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>